Cic. is dealing only with misfortunes that befell Pompey personally; and that his property might have been seized by others at the time when it was seized, even though he had died much earlier. deleti, though supported by several editors, seems irreconcilable with the fact that one son was alive when Cic. wrote this passage. Mo. says ‘quasi dixerit paene deleti’: this would be the rhetorical use of the plural. And even though deleti were justified the other objections quoted above from Hei. would still apply.
